We enjoy coming to Hikari for AYCE.
I am surprised by some of the comments about the food not being fresh because we have always experienced the opposite.
We are recreational fishermen from Hawaii and recognize that unless we catch it ourselves, you will not find seafood as fresh in Hawaii.
(They ship it out almost immediately to every-other-place on the globe.
)  Nimo and her husband are the owners, they have always engaged us in conversation as we have visited frequently.
We prefer to sit at the sushi bar because we are able to order directly from the sushi chef and our food is served up almost before you can finish explaining what it is that you want to eat.
My personal favorites are the uni and ikura, because at home they are outrageously priced.
My husband and I both commented that on our last visit, 12-09-13, the uni was exceptionally sweet and buttery.
Yes, there are color variations with uni, but that does not necessarily mean that the darker it is the older it is.
I love their hamachi and prefer it nigiri rather than sashimi.
I found that the fish was always hiding the sushi rice below as the slices were generous and eating it in proper fashion, I place the entire piece into my mouth at once.
I've tried a few other sushi-type places in Vegas, but I would always return to Hikari.
My only other comment was that the sauce on the oysters this visit was a little less seasoned, but then again, I was getting on a plane in a few hours and thought twice before ordering them.
They were not a problem as they were fresh.
Being somewhat experienced with seafood, we understand that it takes only one bad piece to create havoc on the rest and anyone's gastrointestinal tract and fortunately that has not happened to us after dining at Hikari.
My conclusion, the desert ships, flies, trucks in their seafood and I have not been disappointed because it has probably only been out of the water 2-3 days tops.
Back home, unless you caught it yourself, it's probably closer to 5-6 days out of the water, as the exports and top restaurants get the freshest catches.
As for dessert, I enjoy their tempura ice cream.
It may not move mountains, but it is a nice meal ending, palate cleansing treat.

